litecoin-seeder
===============

Litecoin-seeder is a crawler for the Litecoin network, which exposes a list
of reliable nodes via a built-in DNS server.

Features:
* regularly revisits known nodes to check their availability
* bans nodes after enough failures, or bad behaviour
* accepts nodes down to v0.5.0 to request new IP addresses from,
  but only reports good post-v0.6.9 nodes.
* keeps statistics over (exponential) windows of 2 hours, 8 hours,
  1 day and 1 week, to base decisions on.
* very low memory (a few tens of megabytes) and cpu requirements.
* crawlers run in parallel (by default 96 threads simultaneously).

REQUIREMENTS
------------

$ sudo apt-get install build-essential libboost-all-dev libssl-dev

USAGE
-----

Assuming you want to run a dns seed on dnsseed.example.com, you will
need an authorative NS record in example.com's domain record, pointing
to for example vps.example.com:

$ dig -t NS dnsseed.example.com

;; ANSWER SECTION
dnsseed.example.com.   86400    IN      NS     vps.example.com.

On the system vps.example.com, you can now run dnsseed:

./dnsseed -h dnsseed.example.com -n vps.example.com

If you want the DNS server to report SOA records, please provide an
e-mail address (with the @ part replaced by .) using -m.

COMPILING
---------

Compiling will require boost and ssl.  On debian systems, these are provided
by `libboost-dev` and `libssl-dev` respectively.

$ make

This will produce the `dnsseed` binary.

BLACKLISTING
------------

`dnsseed` can suppress nodes from DNS responses using a local blacklist file,
DNSBL lookups, or both. Blacklist checks are applied when peers are added and
when DNS answer caches are built. DNSBL checks run in a background thread; they
are not performed while answering DNS requests.

For a static blacklist, create a file containing one IP address or CIDR range
per line. `#` starts a comment.

Example `blacklist.txt`:

```
# Exact IPs
203.0.113.10

# IPv4 and IPv6 ranges
198.51.100.0/24
2001:4860:4860::/48
```

Run with:

```
./dnsseed -h dnsseed.example.com -n vps.example.com -m hostmaster.example.com \
  --blacklist blacklist.txt
```

For DNSBL-based suppression, pass one or more DNSBL zones:

```
./dnsseed -h dnsseed.example.com -n vps.example.com -m hostmaster.example.com \
  --dnsbl zen.spamhaus.org \
  --dnsbl b.barracudacentral.org \
  --dnsbl all.spamrats.com
```

DNSBLs are checked against IPv4 nodes by reversing the octets and querying the
zone. For example `203.0.113.10` is checked as:

```
10.113.0.203.zen.spamhaus.org
```

A response in `127.0.0.0/8` is treated as listed. For Spamhaus, responses in
`127.255.255.0/24` are treated as query/configuration errors, not listings.
This matters because Spamhaus may return `127.255.255.254` when DNSBL queries
arrive through a public or open resolver.

Use a local recursive resolver or Spamhaus DQS for production. Avoid relying on
large public resolvers such as `1.1.1.1` or `8.8.8.8` for DNSBL checks; they
can produce blocked, rewritten, or false-negative responses. To force a
specific resolver:

```
./dnsseed -h dnsseed.example.com -n vps.example.com -m hostmaster.example.com \
  --dnsbl zen.spamhaus.org \
  --dnsbl-resolver 127.0.0.1:53
```

The blacklist file is reloaded and DNSBL entries are refreshed every 3600
seconds by default. Adjust the interval with:

```
--blacklist-refresh 1800
```

To audit DNSBL suppression decisions and refresh progress, append refresh status
and state changes to a separate log:

```
./dnsseed -h dnsseed.example.com -n vps.example.com -m hostmaster.example.com \
  --dnsbl zen.spamhaus.org \
  --blacklist-log dnsseed.blacklist.log
```

The log records refresh start/progress/finish lines plus DNSBL transitions. It
does not rewrite the same listed peers on every refresh. Example entries:

```
2026-05-31T05:16:55Z refresh-start peers=321 ipv4=321 zones=2 file_entries=0
2026-05-31T05:16:58Z refresh-progress processed=50/321 checked=50 errors=0 listed=1
2026-05-31T05:17:00Z listed 203.0.113.10 zen.spamhaus.org=127.0.0.2
2026-05-31T05:17:08Z refresh-finish processed=321/321 checked=321 errors=0 listed=7 file_entries=0 dnsbl_listed=7
2026-05-31T06:17:00Z unlisted 203.0.113.10
```

TESTING
-------

It's sometimes useful to test `dnsseed` locally to ensure it's giving good
output (either as part of development or sanity checking). You can inspect
`dnsseed.dump` to inspect all nodes being tracked for crawling, or you can
issue DNS requests directly. Example:

$ dig @:: -p 15353 dnsseed.example.com
       ^       ^    ^
       |       |    |__ Should match the host (-h) argument supplied to dnsseed
       |       |
       |       |_______ Port number (example uses the user space port; see below)
       |
       |_______________ Explicitly call the DNS server on localhost


RUNNING AS NON-ROOT
-------------------

Typically, you'll need root privileges to listen to port 53 (name service).

One solution is using an iptables rule (Linux only) to redirect it to
a non-privileged port:

$ iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p udp --dport 53 -j REDIRECT --to-port 15353

If properly configured, this will allow you to run dnsseed in userspace, using
the -p 15353 option.

Another solution is allowing a binary to bind to ports < 1024 with setcap (IPv6 access-safe)

$ setcap 'cap_net_bind_service=+ep' /path/to/dnsseed
